05779nam a22009015i 9781501752452DE-B159720210526051534.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210526t20202020nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2020005738  a97815017524527 a10.1515/97815017524522doi  a(DE-B1597)546016  a(OCoLC)1141985386  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aPN51 4aPN51b.T665 2020 7aLIT0040202bisacsh04a809/.0472231 aTrask, Michael, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aIdeal Minds :bRaising Consciousness in the Antisocial Seventies /cMichael Trask. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2020] 4cÂ©2020  a1 online resource (258 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: From Consciousness- Raising to Neo-idealism -- t1. Artificial Intelligence and the Rise of the Meritocracy -- t2. Radical Ecology's Mindfulness -- t3. That Seventies Cult -- t4. Millennial America and the World to Come -- tAfterword: The Marketization of Everything -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the wake of the 1960s, that decade's focus on consciousness-raising transformed into an array of intellectual projects far afield of movement politics. The mind's powers came to preoccupy a range of thinkers and writers: ethicists pursuing contractual theories of justice, radical ecologists interested in the paleolithic brain, seventies cultists, and the devout of both evangelical and New Age persuasions. In Ideal Minds, Michael Trask presents a boldly revisionist argument about the revival of subjectivity in postmodern American culture, connecting familiar figures within the seventies intellectual landscape who share a commitment to what he calls "neo-idealism" as a weapon in the struggle against discredited materialist and behaviorist worldviews.In a heterodox intellectual and literary history of the 1970s, Ideal Minds mixes ideas from cognitive science, philosophy of mind, moral philosophy, deep ecology, political theory, science fiction, neoclassical economics, and the sociology of religion. Trask also delves into the decade's more esoteric branches of learning, including Scientology, anarchist theory, rapture prophesies, psychic channeling, and neo-Malthusianism. Through this investigation, Trask argues that a dramatic inflation in the value of consciousness and autonomy beginning in the 1970s accompanied a growing argument about the state's inability to safeguard such values. Ultimately, the thinkers Trask analyzes-John Rawls, Arne Neiss, L. Ron Hubbard, Hal Lindsey, Philip Dick, Ursula Le Guin, Edward Abbey, William Burroughs, John Irving, and James Merrill-found alternatives to statism in conditions that would lend intellectual support to the consolidation of these concepts in the radical free market ideologies of the 1980s.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aAutonomy (Philosophy)xHistoryy1971- 0aAutonomy (Philosophy)xHistoryy1971-. 0aLibertarianism in literature. 0aLiteraturexPhilosophyy1971- 0aLiteraturexPhilosophyy1971-. 0aNeoliberalism in popular culture. 0aNineteen seventiesxPhilosophy. 0aSelf-consciousness (Awareness)xPhilosophyy1971- 0aSelf-consciousness (Awareness)xPhilosophyy1971-. 0aSocial valuesy1971- 0aSocial valuesy1971-. 4aAmerican Studies. 4aLiterary Studies. 4aU.S. History. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCOR eBook-Package Pilot Project 2020z978311069046008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG0